<TITLE> Iran hangs two Afghans for raping Dutch woman </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TEHRAN, Nov 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iran publicly hanged two Afghans for the rape of a Dutch woman on Wednesday, state news agency IRNA said, the latest execution in what the government calls a crackdown on immoral behaviour. The two were put to death in a square in the city of Saveh, southwest of the capital Tehran. Saveh Public prosecutor Reza Shahkarami did not give details of the case and the Dutch embassy in Tehran was not immediately available for comment. The number of executions in Iran, many in public, has risen since July with the launch of the crackdown. Police have arrested dozens of murderers, rapists and drug traffickers. Rights group Amnesty International accuses Iran of having one of the highest rates of capital punishment in the world. It said in September that 210 people had been executed so far this year, compared with 177 for all of 2006. Iran rejects criticism of its human rights record, and accuses Western countries of double standards. Murder, rape, adultery, armed robbery, apostasy and drug smuggling are all punishable by death under Iran's sharia law, imposed after the 1979 Islamic revolution. Up to two million Afghans are believed to be living in Iran, having fled the conflict in their homeland, although many have either returned voluntarily or been expelled since the 2001 overthrow of the Taliban. Those who remain often work as day labourers and live in pover
